Comment (src/views/__tests__/NotificationsView.spec.ts:1166):
This test enables auto-refresh and ends with the Deliveries tab active, which (by design) restarts the 30s interval. Because the wrapper isn’t unmounted, that interval can keep running after the test finishes and cause cross-test flakiness/leaked timers. Consider unmounting the wrapper at the end of this test (or disabling auto-refresh / switching away from Deliveries) so `onUnmounted()` clears the interval.

Implementation guidance: In src/views/admin/NotificationsView.vue, update loadJobs(cursor?: string) so a fresh non-paginated load cannot leave stale pagination state behind. When starting a latest fresh load with no cursor, clear jobsNextCursor.value to null before issuing the request, while preserving existing jobs during the loading state if that is the current UX. In the catch block, after confirming requestSequence is still current, if !cursor then clear both jobs.value and jobsNextCursor.value. Keep the existing request-sequence checks so stale requests still cannot mutate jobs, jobsError, jobsNextCursor, hasLoadedJobs, or jobsLoading.
Implementation guidance: In src/views/__tests__/NotificationsView.spec.ts, update the test named 'lazy-loads operational tabs and pauses job auto-refresh outside deliveries' to clean up its mounted wrapper after enabling auto-refresh and returning to the Deliveries tab. The simplest safe change is to call wrapper.unmount() at the end of the test after the final expect(mockJobsGet).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(3). If you restructure, ensure unmount still runs after the assertions and do not remove the existing vi.useRealTimers() afterEach.
